Strange runes and pictographs, likely arcane in nature, have been scorched into the sides of this hide-covered strongbox.
A trophy for slaying a medusa. Whilst more effective when the eye is within the sockets of a medusa, they still provide its use for turning creatures into stone.

A trophy for those who have slain a tendriculous, a plant creature whose origins in the Realms were uncertain. These creatures were mounds of vegetation, supported by various branches and vines. Their masses had a large opening that was filled with sharp branches and horns, acting sort of like teeth. This piece of the tendriculous vine has mulitple uses related to nature.

An orb carried by a Wereshark. Likely found from whatever mystical depths of the Sea of Swords, this prize now belongs to you! It has the ability to wrap one's lungs in water, deadly for any land dweller.

A magical trinket used to help the user blend in the shadows or their general surroundings, whilst bypassing all the traps that my guard one from an assassin! A prize for defeating a petty and rogue killer.
A trophy for slaying a black pudding ooze. Coat yourself in the slime to release some of it's acidic properties, to coat yourself from any harm. A hazard to use!
The remains of an obsidian golem. Hard to smash, with bountiful of backlash from whatever almighty enchantment was laid onto it. This obsidian core has some energy left within it to ward the bearer.
The essence of a dead Nighthaunt. Dust yourself in its shavings to conceal yourself from friend and foe alike! Suitable for all adventurer's and the ilk for their endeavours.

Nishruus resembled red spheres that glowed and pulsed regularly. They were large creatures that had mist-like forms, and were sometimes referred to as "magic-eaters". This is the leftover essence of a slain magic-eater.
A precious prize held by a creature who had claimed the soul of a person foolish enough to make a deal with it. This enchanted gem has the ability to bind or call forth outsiders.
The bone of an undead abomination, a creature composed of bone and flesh. Still carrying the negative energies since its creation, it can be used to drain the energy of any life nearby.

A trophy for slaying a cyclopes. This eye was rumored to cause fear in any who looked at it. Their single eye gave them poor depth perception, however, and therefore they couldn't use missile weapons very well.
A tome carried by a green hag, known for their prowess in the arcane among many things. This prized trophy holds nothing more than the basic spells for summoning creatures!

Urns are valued in Mulan culture for carrying the ashes of the deceased or simply providing a container for ritual ingredients. This particular urn has been tainted to help keep the undead revigorated, and to give a dose of something painful.
A trophy for slaying an ogre. He once carried about a horn used to call for aid in times of distress, which is now yours! Even putting this against your ears makes everything sound clearer.
A rune stone plucked from a poor adventuring druid who wandered the forest the owlbear had hunted in. This rune provides the balance needed to heal mounds and lower one's resistance from magic.
An enchanted stone from an Earth Drake. Rubbing the stone onto the surface of any skin, attire or plate of armour coats it into stone.

The remains of a shambling mound after its defeat. These vicious beings  feed on the flesh and blood of living creatures they had engulfed and crushed within their own bodies. Made even more ferocious by an unknown being, this rock is left with residue magic.
A leftover brooch from a vanquished banshee. The gem within the brooch contains the negative energy that once stirred the unfortunate soul. Quite deadly when used irresponsibly.

A trophy snatched from a harpy. It seems like the original bearer of this trinket believed their mind would be protected from the captivating song of a harpy. However, it seems they needed more protection than that!
The charm of a sorceress. As any mage who specialises in evocation would need to worry about being exploded by their own spells. A prize after defeating her!
The core of an ice fiend. Holding onto it can allow the user to protect themselves from the harsh environment around them, and any elemental hazards that may come their way.
A prize for those worthy, the core of a fire spirit. One can use this precious stone on any metal or wood to impart its ferocious flames onto it! How original for the world of slayers.

Spellcasters among the kind of Tanarukk, a breed of orc whose blood had been tainted by an evil outsider, were known as firespeakers. They were capable of manipulating fire. This rune was clearly created for their endeavours!

A rune carried by a Belker, a creature of smoke that had an appearance evocative of fiends. This trophy can be used to invoke a gust of wind, and provides a light swirling aura of wind at the wielder's wake, purely for vanity!
